I remember the Rennaissance man of music, Leonard Bernstein, from October 1948. I 
was an American volunteer in the Israeli army. Once, courtesy of the Israeli equivalent to 
the USO, I attended a performance of the Israel Philharmonic when Bernstein was guest 
conductor.

Black-tie patrons and soldiers in fatigues comprised the audience. The program included 
Beethoven's emotional Fifth Symphony. Intermittently for most of the symphony, we 
could hear machine-gun fire from the Jordanian Legion held sector. The crackling sound 
melded with the music and seemed entirely appropriate to the mood and circumstances. 
Lenny and the orchestra never missed a beat.</SUM>

<SUM
