SUMMARIZER="J">

Seventy-two-year-old maestro, Leonard Bernstein, suffering from emphysema, a lung 
tumor and pulmonary infections, will retire from conducting and performing on the 
piano. He will, however, continue to compose and write and plans to complete a chamber 
music piece, a musical, and his memoirs.

Possibly Bernstein will participate in an AIDS benefit at Carnegie Hall on Oct. 28, but 
other appearances have been canceled.

Bernstein published his first composition in 1942 and conducted his first symphony in 
1944. From 1958 to 1969, he directed the New York Philharmonic. In 1969, he became 
the Philharmonic's laureate conductor for life.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d072"
