SUMMARIZER="J">

Brilliant and flamboyant Leonard Bernstein, the first internationally acclaimed American 
maestro, was buried today at Greenwood Cemetery in Brooklyn. He died Sunday at 72 of 
lung failure.

Flags at Lincoln Center, home of the New York Philharmonic which Bernstein conducted 
from 1958 to 1969, were lowered in his memory. The Philharmonic will perform an all 
Bernstein program beginning Thursday and continuing through Oct. 23. A memorial 
concert is also planned for Nov. 14, the 47th anniversary of Bernstein's Philharmonic 
debut.

In addition to conducting and composing, Bernstein introduced thousands to classical 
music through his Emmy-winning television program, "Young People's Concerts."</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d072"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP881115-0011"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="J">

Leonard Bernstein, 70, returned to Carnegie Hall with the New York Philharmonic 
Monday, 45 years after his triumphant debut with the orchestra. Three Bernstein 
compositions, all played stunningly, formed the program. At intermission, Mrs. Arthur 
Rodzinski, widow of the  Philharmonic music director who hired Bernstein as his 
assistant in 1943, was introduced. Violinist Jacques Margolies, who played in that first 
concert, is still a member of the orchestra and played Monday night. Eight others who 
were members in 1943 went on stage. 

Bernstein, in his 1,215th appearance as Philharmonic conductor, received a silver box 
engraved with a reproduction of Monday evening's program.</SUM>
